## Implementation Details

### Option A: Frontend File Reading (Current Design)
```typescript
import { readDir, readTextFile } from '@tauri-apps/api/fs';
import { homeDir } from '@tauri-apps/api/path';

export interface ConversationEntry {
  event_type: 'message' | 'chunk' | 'command' | 'stderr';
  timestamp: number;
  session_id: string;
  bead_id: string;
  persona: string;
  role?: 'user' | 'assistant';
  content: string;
  metadata?: Record<string, any>;
}

export async function loadSessionHistory(
  sessionId: string, 
  beadId: string
): Promise<Message[]> {
  const home = await homeDir();
  const logPath = `${home}/.bp6/sessions/${beadId}/${sessionId}.jsonl`;

  try {
    const content = await readTextFile(logPath);
    const lines = content.split('\n').filter(l => l.trim());

    const messages: Message[] = [];
    for (const line of lines) {
      const entry: ConversationEntry = JSON.parse(line);
      if (entry.event_type === 'message' && entry.role) {
        messages.push({
          role: entry.role,
          content: entry.content
        });
      }
    }
    return messages;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Failed to load session history:', error);
    return [];
  }
}
```

**IMPORTANT:** Verify Tauri allowlist configuration permits fs access to ~/.bp6/

### Option B: Backend Tauri Command (RECOMMENDED)
Add to Rust backend:
```rust
#[tauri::command]
pub fn load_session_history(session_id: String, bead_id: String)
    -> Result<Vec<Message>, String>
```

This avoids frontend fs permission issues and leverages existing backend logging infrastructure.

